[src:webgpu/api-gpubuffer] This feature is not Baseline because it does not work in some of the most widely-used browsers.
[src:webgpu/api-gpubuffer] The **`GPUBuffer`** interface of the WebGPU API represents a block of memory that can be used to store raw data to use in GPU operations.
[src:webgpu/api-gpubuffer] A `GPUBuffer` object instance is created using the `GPUDevice.createBuffer()` method.
[src:webgpu/api-gpubuffer] A string providing a label that can be used to identify the object, for example in `GPUError` messages or console warnings.
[src:webgpu/api-gpubuffer] An enumerated value representing the mapped state of the `GPUBuffer`.
[src:webgpu/api-gpubuffer] A number representing the length of the `GPUBuffer`'s memory allocation, in bytes.
[src:webgpu/api-gpubuffer] The bitwise flags representing the allowed usages of the `GPUBuffer`.
[src:webgpu/api-gpubuffer] Returns an `ArrayBuffer` containing the mapped contents of the `GPUBuffer` in the specified range.
[src:webgpu/api-gpubuffer] Maps the specified range of the `GPUBuffer`.
[src:webgpu/api-gpubuffer] Returns a `Promise` that resolves when the `GPUBuffer`'s content is ready to be accessed with `GPUBuffer.getMappedRange()`.
[src:webgpu/api-gpubuffer] Unmaps the mapped range of the `GPUBuffer`, making its contents available for use by the GPU again.
[src:webgpu/api-gpubuffer] In our basic compute demo, we create an output buffer to read GPU calculations to, and a staging buffer to be mapped for JavaScript access.
[src:webgpu/api-gpudevice] The **`GPUDevice`** interface of the WebGPU API represents a logical GPU device.
[src:webgpu/api-gpudevice] This is the main interface through which the majority of WebGPU functionality is accessed.
[src:webgpu/api-gpudevice] A `GPUDevice` object is requested using the `GPUAdapter.requestDevice()` method.
[src:webgpu/api-gpudevice] A `GPUAdapterInfo` object containing identifying information about the device's originating adapter.
[src:webgpu/api-gpudevice] A `GPUSupportedFeatures` object that describes additional functionality supported by the device.
[src:webgpu/api-gpudevice] A `GPUSupportedLimits` object that describes the limits supported by the device.
[src:webgpu/api-gpudevice] Contains a `Promise` that remains pending throughout the device's lifetime and resolves with a `GPUDeviceLostInfo` object when the device is lost.
[src:webgpu/api-gpudevice] Returns the primary `GPUQueue` for the device.
[src:webgpu/api-gpudevice] Creates a `GPUBindGroup` based on a `GPUBindGroupLayout` that defines a set of resources to be bound together in a group and how those resources are used in shader stages.
[src:webgpu/api-gpudevice] Creates a `GPUBindGroupLayout` that defines the structure and purpose of related GPU resources such as buffers that will be used in a pipeline, and is used as a template when creating `GPUBindGroup`s.
[src:webgpu/api-gpudevice] Creates a `GPUBuffer` in which to store raw data to use in GPU operations.
[src:webgpu/api-gpudevice] Creates a `GPUCommandEncoder`, which is used to encode commands to be issued to the GPU.
[src:webgpu/api-gpudevice] Creates a `GPUComputePipeline` that can control the compute shader stage and be used in a `GPUComputePassEncoder`.
[src:webgpu/api-gpudevice] Returns a `Promise` that fulfills with a `GPUComputePipeline`, which can control the compute shader stage and be used in a `GPUComputePassEncoder`, once the pipeline can be used without any stalling.
[src:webgpu/api-gpudevice] Creates a `GPUPipelineLayout` that defines the `GPUBindGroupLayout`s used by a pipeline.
[src:webgpu/api-gpudevice] `GPUBindGroup`s used with the pipeline during command encoding must have compatible `GPUBindGroupLayout`s.
[src:webgpu/api-gpudevice] Creates a `GPUQuerySet` that can be used to record the results of queries on passes, such as occlusion or timestamp queries.
[src:webgpu/api-gpudevice] Creates a `GPURenderBundleEncoder` that can be used to pre-record bundles of commands.
[src:webgpu/api-gpudevice] These can be reused in `GPURenderPassEncoder`s via the `executeBundles()` method, as many times as required.
[src:webgpu/api-gpudevice] Creates a `GPURenderPipeline` that can control the vertex and fragment shader stages and be used in a `GPURenderPassEncoder` or `GPURenderBundleEncoder`.
[src:webgpu/api-gpudevice] Returns a `Promise` that fulfills with a `GPURenderPipeline`, which can control the vertex and fragment shader stages and be used in a `GPURenderPassEncoder` or `GPURenderBundleEncoder`, once the pipeline can be used without any stalling.
[src:webgpu/api-gpudevice] Creates a `GPUSampler`, which controls how shaders transform and filter texture resource data.
[src:webgpu/api-gpudevice] Creates a `GPUShaderModule` from a string of WGSL source code.
[src:webgpu/api-gpudevice] Creates a `GPUTexture` in which to store texture data to use in GPU rendering operations.
[src:webgpu/api-gpudevice] Destroys the device, preventing further operations on it.
[src:webgpu/api-gpudevice] Takes an `HTMLVideoElement` as an input and returns a `GPUExternalTexture` wrapper object containing a snapshot of the video that can be used in GPU rendering operations.
[src:webgpu/api-gpudevice] Pops an existing GPU error scope from the error scope stack and returns a `Promise` that resolves to an object (`GPUInternalError`, `GPUOutOfMemoryError`, or `GPUValidationError`) describing the first error captured in the scope, or `null` if no error occurred.
[src:webgpu/api-gpudevice] Pushes a new GPU error scope onto the device's error scope stack, allowing you to capture errors of a particular type.
[src:webgpu/api-gpudevice] Fired when an error is thrown that has not been observed by a GPU error scope, to provide a way to report unexpected errors.
[src:webgpu/api-gpudevice] Known error cases should be handled using `pushErrorScope()` and `popErrorScope()`.
[src:webgpu/api-gpuqueue] The **`GPUQueue`** interface of the WebGPU API controls execution of encoded commands on the GPU.
[src:webgpu/api-gpuqueue] A device's primary queue is accessed via the `GPUDevice.queue` property.
[src:webgpu/api-gpuqueue] Copies a snapshot taken from a source image, video, or canvas into a given `GPUTexture`.
[src:webgpu/api-gpuqueue] Returns a `Promise` that resolves when all the work submitted to the GPU via this `GPUQueue` at the point the method is called has been processed.
[src:webgpu/api-gpuqueue] Schedules the execution of command buffers represented by one or more `GPUCommandBuffer` objects by the GPU.
[src:webgpu/api-gpuqueue] Writes a provided data source into a given `GPUBuffer`.
[src:webgpu/api-gpuqueue] Writes a provided data source into a given `GPUTexture`.
[src:webgpu/api-gpuqueue] To use this data in a render pipeline, we need to put it into a `GPUBuffer`.
[src:webgpu/api-gpuqueue] Later on, a set of commands is encoded into a `GPUCommandBuffer` using the `GPUCommandEncoder.finish()` method.
[src:webgpu/api-gpuqueue] The command buffer is then passed into the queue via a `submit()` call, ready to be processed by the GPU.
[src:webgpu/api-webgpu-api] The **WebGPU API** enables web developers to use the underlying system's GPU (Graphics Processing Unit) to carry out high-performance computations and draw complex images that can be rendered in the browser.
[src:webgpu/api-webgpu-api] WebGPU is the successor to WebGL, providing better compatibility with modern GPUs, support for general-purpose GPU computations, faster operations, and access to more advanced GPU features.
[src:webgpu/api-webgpu-api] It is fair to say that WebGL revolutionized the web in terms of graphical capabilities after it first appeared around 2011.
[src:webgpu/api-webgpu-api] WebGL is a JavaScript port of the OpenGL ES 2.0 graphics library, allowing web pages to pass rendering computations directly to the device's GPU to be processed at very high speeds, and render the result inside a `<canvas>` element.
[src:webgpu/api-webgpu-api] WebGL and the GLSL language used to write WebGL shader code are complex, so several WebGL libraries have been created to make WebGL apps easier to write: Popular examples include Three.js, Babylon.js, and PlayCanvas.
[src:webgpu/api-webgpu-api] Developers have used these tools to build immersive web-based 3D games, music videos, training and modeling tools, VR and AR experiences, and more.
[src:webgpu/api-webgpu-api] WebGPU addresses these issues, providing an updated general-purpose architecture compatible with modern GPU APIs, which feels more "webby".
[src:webgpu/api-webgpu-api] It supports graphic rendering, but also has first-class support for GPGPU computations.
[src:webgpu/api-webgpu-api] Rendering of individual objects is significantly cheaper on the CPU side, and it supports modern GPU rendering features such as compute-based particles and post-processing filters like color effects, sharpening, and depth-of-field simulation.
[src:webgpu/api-webgpu-api] In addition, it can handle expensive computations such as culling and skinned model transformation directly on the GPU.
[src:webgpu/api-webgpu-api] There are several layers of abstraction between a device GPU and a web browser running the WebGPU API.
[src:webgpu/api-webgpu-api] A logical device — represented by a `GPUDevice` object instance — is the basis from which a web app accesses all WebGPU functionality.
[src:webgpu/api-webgpu-api] You access an adapter via the `GPU.requestAdapter()` method.
[src:webgpu/api-webgpu-api] This method accepts an optional settings object allowing you to request, for example, a compatibility mode, high-performance, or low-energy adapter.
[src:webgpu/api-webgpu-api] If this is not included, the device will provide access to the default adapter, which is good enough for most purposes.
[src:webgpu/api-webgpu-api] A device can be requested via `GPUAdapter.requestDevice()`.
[src:webgpu/api-webgpu-api] This method also accepts an options object (referred to as a descriptor), which can be used to specify the exact features and limits you want the logical device to have.
[src:webgpu/api-webgpu-api] If this is not included, the supplied device will have a reasonable general-purpose spec that is good enough for most purposes.
[src:webgpu/api-webgpu-api] By default, a `GPUAdapter` supports all core WebGPU features and limits, which allows applications to support devices with modern platform graphics APIs.
[src:webgpu/api-webgpu-api] It is possible to opt WebGPU into "compatibility mode", which specifies that the `GPUAdapter` will support a restricted subset of the WebGPU API capable of running in older graphics APIs such as OpenGL ES 3.1 and Direct3D 11.
[src:webgpu/api-webgpu-api] The exact restrictions of compatibility mode are detailed at WebGPU Compatibility Mode.
[src:webgpu/api-webgpu-api] Restricted applications are still valid WebGPU core applications due to supporting a subset of core WebGPU, and will therefore run on all browsers that support core WebGPU, even if they don't explicitly support compatibility mode.
[src:webgpu/api-webgpu-api] A `GPUAdapter` or `GPUDevice` that supports core WebGPU will have the `core-features-and-limits` feature available (see `GPUSupportedFeatures`).
[src:webgpu/api-webgpu-api] See also Using compatibility mode only if necessary.
[src:webgpu/api-webgpu-api] A pipeline is a logical structure containing programmable stages that are completed to get your program's work done.
[src:webgpu/api-webgpu-api] The shaders mentioned above are sets of instructions processed by the GPU.
[src:webgpu/api-webgpu-api] WebGPU shaders are written in a low-level Rust-like language called WebGPU Shading Language (WGSL).
[src:webgpu/api-webgpu-api] Get and configure the canvas context: Get the `webgpu` context of a `<canvas>` element and configure it to receive information on what graphics to render from your GPU logical device.
[src:webgpu/api-webgpu-api] This step is not necessary if your app has no graphical output, such as one that only uses compute pipelines.
[src:webgpu/api-webgpu-api] Create resources containing your data: The data that you want processed by your pipelines needs to be stored in GPU buffers or textures to be accessed by your app.
[src:webgpu/api-webgpu-api] Create pipelines: Define pipeline descriptors that describe the desired pipelines in detail, including the required data structure, bindings, shaders, and resource layouts, then create pipelines from them.
[src:webgpu/api-webgpu-api] Our basic demos only contain a single pipeline, but non-trivial apps will usually contain multiple pipelines for different purposes.
[src:webgpu/api-webgpu-api] Create a pass encoder object on which compute/render commands are issued.
[src:webgpu/api-webgpu-api] Run commands to specify which pipelines to use, what buffer(s) to get the required data from, how many drawing operations to run (in the case of render pipelines), etc.
[src:webgpu/api-webgpu-api] Finalize the command list and encapsulate it in a command buffer.
[src:webgpu/api-webgpu-api] Submit the command buffer to the GPU via the logical device's command queue.
[src:webgpu/api-webgpu-api] In the sections below, we will examine a basic render pipeline demo, to allow you to explore what it requires.
[src:webgpu/api-webgpu-api] Later on, we'll also examine a basic compute pipeline example, looking at how it differs from the render pipeline.
[src:webgpu/api-webgpu-api] In our basic render demo we give a `<canvas>` element a solid blue background and draw a triangle onto it.
[src:webgpu/api-webgpu-api] The vertex shader stage (`@vertex` block) accepts a chunk of data containing a position and a color, positions the vertex according to the given position, interpolates the color, then passes the data along to the fragment shader stage.
[src:webgpu/api-webgpu-api] The fragment shader stage (`@fragment` block) accepts the data from the vertex shader stage and colors the vertex according to the given color.
[src:webgpu/api-webgpu-api] To make your shader code available to WebGPU, you have to put it inside a `GPUShaderModule` via a `GPUDevice.createShaderModule()` call, passing your shader code as a property inside a descriptor object.
[src:webgpu/api-webgpu-api] In a render pipeline, we need to specify somewhere to render the graphics to.
[src:webgpu/api-webgpu-api] In this case we are getting a reference to an onscreen `<canvas>` element then calling `HTMLCanvasElement.getContext()` with a parameter of `webgpu` to return its GPU context (a `GPUCanvasContext` instance).
[src:webgpu/api-webgpu-api] From there, we configure the context with a call to `GPUCanvasContext.configure()`, passing it an options object containing the `GPUDevice` that the rendering information will come from, the format the textures will have, and the alpha mode to use when rendering semi-transparent textures.
[src:webgpu/api-webgpu-api] Next we will provide our WebGPU program with our data, in a form it can use.
[src:webgpu/api-webgpu-api] Our data is initially provided in a `Float32Array`, which contains 8 data points for each triangle vertex — X, Y, Z, W for position, and R, G, B, A for color.
[src:webgpu/api-webgpu-api] We need to get our data into a `GPUBuffer`.
[src:webgpu/api-webgpu-api] Behind the scenes, this type of buffer is stored in memory very tightly integrated with the GPU's cores to allow for the desired high performance processing.
[src:webgpu/api-webgpu-api] As a side effect, this memory can't be accessed by processes running on the host system, like the browser.
[src:webgpu/api-webgpu-api] The `GPUBuffer` is created via a call to `GPUDevice.createBuffer()`.
[src:webgpu/api-webgpu-api] We give it a size equal to the length of the `vertices` array so it can contain all the data, and `VERTEX` and `COPY_DST` usage flags to indicate that the buffer will be used as a vertex buffer and the destination of copy operations.
[src:webgpu/api-webgpu-api] We could handle getting our data into the `GPUBuffer` using a mapping operation, like we use in the compute pipeline example to read data from the GPU back to JavaScript.
[src:webgpu/api-webgpu-api] However, in this case we are going to use the handy `GPUQueue.writeBuffer()` convenience method, which takes as its parameters the buffer to write to, the data source to write from, an offset value for each, and the size of data to write (we've specified the whole length of the array).
[src:webgpu/api-webgpu-api] The browser then works out the most efficient way to handle writing the data.
[src:webgpu/api-webgpu-api] Now we've got our data into a buffer, the next part of the setup is to actually create our pipeline, ready to be used for rendering.
[src:webgpu/api-webgpu-api] First of all, we create an object that describes the required layout of our vertex data.
[src:webgpu/api-webgpu-api] This perfectly describes what we saw earlier on in our `vertices` array and vertex shader stage — each vertex has position and color data.
[src:webgpu/api-webgpu-api] Both are formatted in `float32x4` format (which maps to the WGSL `vec4<f32>` type), and the color data starts at an offset of 16 bytes into each vertex.
[src:webgpu/api-webgpu-api] `arrayStride` specifies the stride, meaning the number of bytes making up each vertex, and `stepMode` specifies that the data should be fetched per-vertex.
[src:webgpu/api-webgpu-api] Next, we create a descriptor object that specifies the configuration of our render pipeline stages.
[src:webgpu/api-webgpu-api] For both the shader stages, we specify the `GPUShaderModule` that the relevant code can be found in (`shaderModule`), and the name of the function that acts as the entry point for each stage.
[src:webgpu/api-webgpu-api] In addition, in the case of the vertex shader stage we provide our `vertexBuffers` object to provide the expected state of our vertex data.
[src:webgpu/api-webgpu-api] And in the case of our fragment shader stage, we provide an array of color target states that indicate the specified rendering format (this matches the format specified in our canvas context config earlier).
[src:webgpu/api-webgpu-api] We also specify a `primitive` object, which in this case just states the type of primitive we will be drawing, and a `layout` of `auto`.
[src:webgpu/api-webgpu-api] The `layout` property defines the layout (structure, purpose, and type) of all the GPU resources (buffers, textures, etc.) used during the execution of the pipeline.
[src:webgpu/api-webgpu-api] In more complex apps, this would take the form of a `GPUPipelineLayout` object, created using `GPUDevice.createPipelineLayout()` (you can see an example in our Basic compute pipeline), which allows the GPU to figure out how to run the pipeline most efficiently ahead of time.
[src:webgpu/api-webgpu-api] However, we are specifying the `auto` value, which will cause the pipeline to generate an implicit bind group layout based on any bindings defined in the shader code.
[src:webgpu/api-webgpu-api] Finally, we can create a `GPURenderPipeline` based on our `pipelineDescriptor` object, by passing it in as a parameter to a `GPUDevice.createRenderPipeline()` method call.
[src:webgpu/api-webgpu-api] Now that all the setup is done, we can actually run a rendering pass and draw something onto our `<canvas>`.
[src:webgpu/api-webgpu-api] To encode any commands to be later issued to the GPU, you need to create a `GPUCommandEncoder` instance, which is done using a `GPUDevice.createCommandEncoder()` call.
[src:webgpu/api-webgpu-api] Next up we start the rendering pass running by creating a `GPURenderPassEncoder` instance with a `GPUCommandEncoder.beginRenderPass()` call.
[src:webgpu/api-webgpu-api] This method takes a descriptor object as a parameter, the only mandatory property of which is a `colorAttachments` array.
[src:webgpu/api-webgpu-api] That the view should be "cleared" to a specified color once loaded and before any drawing takes place.
[src:webgpu/api-webgpu-api] This is what causes the blue background behind the triangle.
[src:webgpu/api-webgpu-api] That the value of the current rendering pass should be stored for this color attachment.
[src:webgpu/api-webgpu-api] `GPURenderPassEncoder.setVertexBuffer()` is called with our `vertexBuffer` object as a parameter to act as the data source to pass to the pipeline to render.
[src:webgpu/api-webgpu-api] The first parameter is the slot to set the vertex buffer for, and is a reference to the index of the element in the `vertexBuffers` array which describes this buffer's layout.
[src:webgpu/api-webgpu-api] `GPURenderPassEncoder.draw()` sets the drawing in motion.
[src:webgpu/api-webgpu-api] There is data for three vertices inside our `vertexBuffer`, so we set a vertex count value of `3` to draw them all.
[src:webgpu/api-webgpu-api] To finish encoding the sequence of commands and issue them to the GPU, three more steps are needed.
[src:webgpu/api-webgpu-api] We invoke the `GPUCommandEncoder.finish()` method to complete recording of the issued command sequence and encapsulate it into a `GPUCommandBuffer` object instance.
[src:webgpu/api-webgpu-api] We submit the `GPUCommandBuffer` to the device's command queue (represented by a `GPUQueue` instance) to be sent to the GPU.
[src:webgpu/api-webgpu-api] The device's queue is available via the `GPUDevice.queue` property, and an array of `GPUCommandBuffer` instances can be added to the queue via a `GPUQueue.submit()` call.
[src:webgpu/api-webgpu-api] In our basic compute demo, we get the GPU to calculate some values, store them in an output buffer, copy the data across to a staging buffer, then map that staging buffer so that the data can be read out to JavaScript and logged to the console.
[src:webgpu/api-webgpu-api] The app follows a similar structure to the basic rendering demo.
[src:webgpu/api-webgpu-api] We create a `GPUDevice` reference in the same way as before, and encapsulate our shader code into a `GPUShaderModule` via a `GPUDevice.createShaderModule()` call.
[src:webgpu/api-webgpu-api] In this example we create two `GPUBuffer` instances to handle our data, an `output` buffer to write the GPU calculation results to at high speed, and a `stagingBuffer` that we'll copy the `output` contents to, which can be mapped to allow JavaScript to access the values.
[src:webgpu/api-webgpu-api] When the pipeline is created, we specify a bind group to use for the pipeline.
[src:webgpu/api-webgpu-api] This involves first creating a `GPUBindGroupLayout` (via a call to `GPUDevice.createBindGroupLayout()`) that defines the structure and purpose of GPU resources such as buffers that will be used in this pipeline.
[src:webgpu/api-webgpu-api] This layout is used as a template for bind groups to adhere to.
[src:webgpu/api-webgpu-api] In this case we give the pipeline access to a single memory buffer, tied to binding slot 0 (this matches the relevant binding number in our shader code — `@binding(0)`), usable in the compute stage of the pipeline, and with the buffer's purpose defined as `storage`.
[src:webgpu/api-webgpu-api] Next we create a `GPUBindGroup` by calling `GPUDevice.createBindGroup()`.
[src:webgpu/api-webgpu-api] We pass this method call a descriptor object that specifies the bind group layout to base this bind group on, and the details of the variable to bind to the slot defined in the layout.
[src:webgpu/api-webgpu-api] In this case, we are declaring binding 0, and specifying that the `output` buffer we defined earlier should be bound to it.
[src:webgpu/api-webgpu-api] With the above all in place, we can now create a compute pipeline by calling `GPUDevice.createComputePipeline()`, passing it a pipeline descriptor object.
[src:webgpu/api-webgpu-api] This works in a similar way to creating a render pipeline.
[src:webgpu/api-webgpu-api] We describe the compute shader, specifying what module to find the code in and what the entry point is.
[src:webgpu/api-webgpu-api] We also specify a `layout` for the pipeline, in this case creating a layout based on the `bindGroupLayout` we defined earlier via a `GPUDevice.createPipelineLayout()` call.
[src:webgpu/api-webgpu-api] One difference here from the render pipeline layout is that we are not specifying a primitive type, as we are not drawing anything.
[src:webgpu/api-webgpu-api] Running a compute pass is similar in structure to running a rendering pass, with some different commands.
[src:webgpu/api-webgpu-api] For a start, the pass encoder is created using `GPUCommandEncoder.beginComputePass()`.
[src:webgpu/api-webgpu-api] When issuing the commands, we specify the pipeline to use in the same way as before, using `GPUComputePassEncoder.setPipeline()`.
[src:webgpu/api-webgpu-api] We then however use `GPUComputePassEncoder.setBindGroup()` to specify that we want to use our `bindGroup` to specify the data to use in the calculation, and `GPUComputePassEncoder.dispatchWorkgroups()` to specify the number of GPU workgroups to use to run the calculations.
[src:webgpu/api-webgpu-api] We then signal the end of the render pass command list using `GPURenderPassEncoder.end()`.
[src:webgpu/api-webgpu-api] Before submitting the encoded commands to the GPU for execution using `GPUQueue.submit()`, we copy the contents of the `output` buffer to the `stagingBuffer` buffer using `GPUCommandEncoder.copyBufferToBuffer()`.
[src:webgpu/api-webgpu-api] Once the output data is available in the `stagingBuffer`, we use the `GPUBuffer.mapAsync()` method to map the data to intermediate memory, grab a reference to the mapped range using `GPUBuffer.getMappedRange()`, copy the data into JavaScript, and then log it to the console.
[src:webgpu/api-webgpu-api] We also unmap the `stagingBuffer` once we are finished with it.
[src:webgpu/api-webgpu-api] WebGPU calls are validated asynchronously in the GPU process.
[src:webgpu/api-webgpu-api] If errors are found, the problem call is marked as invalid on the GPU side.
[src:webgpu/api-webgpu-api] If another call is made that relies on the return value of an invalidated call, that object will also be marked as invalid, and so on.
[src:webgpu/api-webgpu-api] For this reason, errors in WebGPU are referred to as "contagious".
[src:webgpu/api-webgpu-api] Each `GPUDevice` instance maintains its own error scope stack.
[src:webgpu/api-webgpu-api] This stack is initially empty, but you can start pushing an error scope to the stack by invoking `GPUDevice.pushErrorScope()` to capture errors of a particular type.
[src:webgpu/api-webgpu-api] Once you are done capturing errors, you can end capture by invoking `GPUDevice.popErrorScope()`.
[src:webgpu/api-webgpu-api] This pops the scope from the stack and returns a `Promise` that resolves to an object (`GPUInternalError`, `GPUOutOfMemoryError`, or `GPUValidationError`) describing the first error captured in the scope, or `null` if no errors were captured.
[src:webgpu/api-webgpu-api] We have attempted to provide useful information to help you understand why errors are occurring in your WebGPU code in "Validation" sections where appropriate, which list criteria to meet to avoid errors.
[src:webgpu/api-webgpu-api] See for example the `GPUDevice.createBindGroup()` Validation section.
[src:webgpu/api-webgpu-api] You can find more information about WebGPU error handling in the explainer — see Object validity and destroyed-ness and Errors.
[src:webgpu/api-webgpu-api] WebGPU Error Handling best practices provides useful real-world examples and advice.
[src:webgpu/api-webgpu-api] The entry point for the API — returns the `GPU` object for the current context.
[src:webgpu/api-webgpu-api] It can be used to return a `GPUAdapter`.
[src:webgpu/api-webgpu-api] From this you can request a `GPUDevice`, adapter info, features, and limits.
[src:webgpu/api-webgpu-api] Contains identifying information about an adapter.
[src:webgpu/api-webgpu-api] A setlike object that describes additional functionality supported by a `GPUAdapter` or `GPUDevice`.
[src:webgpu/api-webgpu-api] Describes the limits supported by a `GPUAdapter` or `GPUDevice`.
[src:webgpu/api-webgpu-api] Invoking `getContext()` with the `"webgpu"` `contextType` returns a `GPUCanvasContext` object instance, which can then be configured with `GPUCanvasContext.configure()`.
[src:webgpu/api-webgpu-api] Represents the WebGPU rendering context of a `<canvas>` element.
[src:webgpu/api-webgpu-api] Represents a block of memory that can be used to store raw data to use in GPU operations.
[src:webgpu/api-webgpu-api] A wrapper object containing an `HTMLVideoElement` snapshot that can be used as a texture in GPU rendering operations.
[src:webgpu/api-webgpu-api] Controls how shaders transform and filter texture resource data.
[src:webgpu/api-webgpu-api] A reference to an internal shader module object, a container for WGSL shader code that can be submitted to the GPU to execution by a pipeline.
[src:webgpu/api-webgpu-api] A container used to store 1D, 2D, or 3D arrays of data, such as images, to use in GPU rendering operations.
[src:webgpu/api-webgpu-api] A view onto some subset of the texture subresources defined by a particular `GPUTexture`.
[src:webgpu/api-webgpu-api] Based on a `GPUBindGroupLayout`, a `GPUBindGroup` defines a set of resources to be bound together in a group and how those resources are used in shader stages.
[src:webgpu/api-webgpu-api] Defines the structure and purpose of related GPU resources such as buffers that will be used in a pipeline, and is used as a template when creating `GPUBindGroup`s.
[src:webgpu/api-webgpu-api] Controls the compute shader stage and can be used in a `GPUComputePassEncoder`.
[src:webgpu/api-webgpu-api] Defines the `GPUBindGroupLayout`s used by a pipeline.
[src:webgpu/api-webgpu-api] Controls the vertex and fragment shader stages and can be used in a `GPURenderPassEncoder` or `GPURenderBundleEncoder`.
[src:webgpu/api-webgpu-api] Represents a recorded list of GPU commands that can be submitted to a `GPUQueue` for execution.
[src:webgpu/api-webgpu-api] Represents a command encoder, used to encode commands to be issued to the GPU.
[src:webgpu/api-webgpu-api] Encodes commands related to controlling the compute shader stage, as issued by a `GPUComputePipeline`.
[src:webgpu/api-webgpu-api] Part of the overall encoding activity of a `GPUCommandEncoder`.
[src:webgpu/api-webgpu-api] controls execution of encoded commands on the GPU.
[src:webgpu/api-webgpu-api] A container for pre-recorded bundles of commands (see `GPURenderBundleEncoder`).
[src:webgpu/api-webgpu-api] Encodes commands related to controlling the vertex and fragment shader stages, as issued by a `GPURenderPipeline`.
[src:webgpu/api-webgpu-api] Used to record the results of queries on passes, such as occlusion or timestamp queries.
[src:webgpu/api-webgpu-api] An array of `GPUCompilationMessage` objects, generated by the GPU shader module compiler to help diagnose problems with shader code.
[src:webgpu/api-webgpu-api] Represents a single informational, warning, or error message generated by the GPU shader module compiler.
[src:webgpu/api-webgpu-api] Returned when the `GPUDevice.lost` `Promise` resolves, providing information as to why the device was lost.
